@my_portal\my_celery.py:1-21
This code sets up a Celery application, which is a distributed task queue system used for asynchronous task execution in Python. The purpose of this code is to configure and initialize the Celery application for a Django project called "my_portal".
The code starts by importing necessary modules and setting the Django settings module for the project. It then creates a Celery instance called "app" and configures it with the settings from the Django project.
The code does not take any direct input, but it relies on the Django project's settings and the presence of task functions defined elsewhere in the project.
The output of this code is a configured Celery application instance that can be used to schedule and execute asynchronous tasks within the Django project.
To achieve its purpose, the code follows these steps:
1. It imports the necessary modules, including the Celery library and a task function called "send_email_notification_to_subscribers" from the "news" app. 2. It sets the Django settings module for the project using the "os.environ.setdefault" function. 3. It creates a Celery instance called "app" and configures it with the settings from the Django project using the "app.config_from_object" method. 4. It tells Celery to automatically discover tasks defined in the Django project using the "app.autodiscover_tasks" method. 5. It sets up the Celery broker URL (the message queue system used by Celery) and serialization settings for tasks and results. 6. It registers the "send_email_notification_to_subscribers" task with the Celery application using the "app.task" decorator.
The code does not involve any complex logic flows or data transformations. Its primary purpose is to set up the Celery application and configure it with the necessary settings and tasks for the Django project.
